In Kirinyaga, the lawmakers received an additional Sh7,719 from the Sh93,322 paid last year.
The 47 county assemblies spent Sh376.68 million against the cumulative annual budget of Sh2.75 billion, which implies a 13.7 percent absorption rate.
This was a decline from last year’s figure of Sh475.41 million, representing a 18.6 percent absorption rate.
Lowest paid counties
MCAs in Marsabit, Tharaka Nithi and Muran’ga counties were paid the least amounts in the region, receiving Sh6,503, Sh24,032 and Sh29,678 respectively.
The figures were significantly lower than what was paid in the same period last year.
In the three months that ended September 2020, Marsabit did not report any expense on MCAs’ allowances.
Tharaka Nithi’s ward representatives received Sh66,487 while their Muran’ga counterparts received Sh98,292.
Meru County’s 69 MCAs received Sh45,449, a significant decrease from the Sh123,767 they received last year. In Embu, the MCAs received Sh30,334, a decline from Sh93,414.
“The county spent Sh3.19million on committee sittings for the 34 MCAs and the speaker against the annual budget allocation of Sh33.54 million. The average monthly sitting allowance was Sh30,334 per MCA,” Ms Nyakan’go said .



